(2) The National Child Welfare Board shall perform the following duties and functions, namely:-

(a) Supervise, coordinate, monitor and evaluate the activities of child development centers and certified institutions;

(b) Disadvantaged children and children in contact with the law and children in conflict with the law-

(i) Providing guidance to those concerned in formulating policies, planning and implementing plans related to reintegration and rehabilitation into family and social life;

(ii) To determine their gender-based numbers and collect information and data on their lifestyles for the purpose of welfare and development and to provide necessary advice to the government in this regard;

(e) to determine, where applicable, the necessary alternative approach or alternative means of care and to review the information and data of the child covered by such approach or care;

(c) Approval of the recommendations of the District Child Welfare Board;

(d) District and Upazila Child Welfare Boards-

(i) Formulate policies and, where necessary, provide recommendations and guidelines;

(ii) Calling for reports from them from time to time regarding their activities and, if necessary, organizing inter-board coordination meetings to coordinate their activities;

(e) To take other measures necessary for the performance of the above-mentioned duties and functions.

If a child is convicted of any offence under this Act or any other law, -

(a) Section 75 of the Penal Code or Section 565 of the Code of Criminal Procedure shall not apply to him;

(b) He shall not be considered disqualified from holding any office in the government or private sector or from contesting any election under any law.

Subject to the provisions of this Act, no person other than the following persons shall be present at the session of the Children's Court, namely:-

(a) the child concerned;

(b) the child's parents and, in the absence of both of them, the guardian or authority having custody of the child or the legal or legitimate guardian or, as the case may be, a member of the extended family;

(c) Officers and employees of the Juvenile Court;

(d) Parties to cases or proceedings brought in the Children's Court, child affairs or related police officers, lawyers involved in the case and other persons directly involved in the case or proceedings, including probation officers; and

(e) A person specifically permitted by the Children's Court to be present or to be present.

(1) If, by reason of any injury or disease to the immature brain, any person

(a) Abnormalities in general gait and posture, which limit daily activities;

(b) the extent of brain damage in such cases does not subsequently decrease or increase; and

(c) Daily functioning can be enhanced by providing appropriate healthcare,

In that case, he will be considered a 'person with cerebral palsy disability'.

(2) The characteristics of disability due to cerebral palsy shall be as follows, namely:

(a) Muscles being too tight or loose;

(b) Inconsistency or limitation in normal movements of the arms or legs;

(c) Imbalance or poor balance in normal movement;

(d) Visual, hearing, intellectual or any other impairment to a greater or lesser degree;

(e) behavioral limitations;

(f) communication restrictions; or

(g) One hand or both hands or one foot or both feet or one hand and foot or both hands and feet are affected.

